04397nam a22006135i 9780822385356DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223853567 a10.1515/97808223853562doi  a(DE-B1597)554162  a(OCoLC)994994872  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0170002bisacsh1 aVillarejo, Amy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLesbian Rule :bCultural Criticism and the Value of Desire /cAmy Villarejo; ed. by Inderpal Grewal, Robyn Wiegman, Caren Kaplan. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (246 p.) :b20 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNext Wave: New Directions in Women's Studies : 4400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Lesbian Rule -- t2. Droits de Regards/Right of Inspection: For Agnes and Inez Albright -- t3. Archiving the Diaspora: A Lesbian Impression -- t4. Absolut Queer: Cuba and its Spectators -- t5. Forbidden Love: Pulp as Lesbian History -- tConclusion: Straight to Video -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith hair slicked back and shirt collar framing her young patrician face, Katherine Hepburn's image in the 1935 film Sylvia Scarlett was seen by many as a lesbian representation. Yet, Amy Villarejo argues, there is no final ground upon which to explain why that image of Hepburn signifies lesbian or why such a cross-dressing Hollywood fantasy edges into collective consciousness as a lesbian narrative. Investigating what allows viewers to perceive an image or narrative as "lesbian," Villarejo presents a theoretical exploration of lesbian visibility. Focusing on images of lesbians in film, she analyzes what these representations contain and their limits. She combines Marxist theories of value with poststructuralist insights to argue that lesbian visibility operates simultaneously as an achievement and a ruse, a possibility for building a new visual politics and away of rendering static and contained what lesbian might mean.Integrating cinema studies, queer and feminist theory, and cultural studies, Villarejo illuminates the contexts within which the lesbian is rendered visible. Toward that end, she analyzes key portrayals of lesbians in public culture, particularly in documentary film. She considers a range of films—from documentaries about Cuba and lesbian pulp fiction to Exile Shanghai and The Brandon Teena Story—and, in doing so, brings to light a nuanced economy of value and desire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCulturexSemiotic models. 0aLesbian feminist theory. 0aLesbianismxPhilosophy. 0aLesbiansxIdentity. 0aMarxist criticism. 0aQueer theory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Lesbian Studies.2bisacsh1 aGrewal, Inderpal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaplan, Caren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWiegman, Robyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822385356zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822385356423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822385356/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles